    lawContext: "Mississippi is not a community property state; a non-liable spouse's separately owned property is generally outside the RCP on a non-joint liability. Mississippi's 2026 individual income tax is a flat 4% on taxable income above the $10,000 single / $20,000 joint exemption (scheduled to step down toward 3% by 2030 and eventually 0% under HB 1), and the IRS allows the state liability as an involuntary deduction when it is being withheld or paid. Mississippi's creditor-side homestead exemption under Miss. Code 85-3-21 protects up to $75,000 in equity on a homestead not exceeding 160 acres, but this exemption does not bind the IRS, which values the home at 80% quick-sale value minus liens.\n\nMississippi does NOT have a formal individual Offer in Compromise statute analogous to the IRS program; the Mississippi Department of Revenue handles hardship on a case-by-case basis, primarily through installment agreements and, in narrow circumstances, penalty waiver rather than principal reduction. Mississippi DOR is also aggressive with driver's-license and professional-license holds under Miss. Code 27-77-12 for delinquent state tax, so many taxpayers pursue federal OIC relief and a state installment plan simultaneously.",
