    lawContext: "Nebraska is not a community property state; the RCP for a non-joint IRS liability normally excludes a non-liable spouse's separately titled property. Nebraska's 2026 individual income tax top rate is 4.55% (reduced from 5.2% in 2025 and scheduled to drop to 3.99% in 2027 under LB 754), and the IRS allows the state liability as an involuntary deduction when it is actually being withheld or paid. Nebraska's general homestead judgment-lien exemption under Neb. Rev. Stat. 40-101 protects only $60,000 of homestead value (limited to 160 acres rural or two lots urban), and the property-tax homestead exemption under Neb. Rev. Stat. 77-3502 et seq. is for seniors, disabled, and qualifying veterans — neither exemption binds the IRS, which values the home at 80% quick-sale value minus liens.\n\nNebraska does NOT have a formal individual Offer in Compromise statute for income tax; the Nebraska Department of Revenue generally uses installment agreements under Neb. Rev. Stat. 77-2711 and case-by-case closing agreements rather than principal reduction. Nebraska DOR does aggressively use state-refund offset, wage garnishment, and driver's-license suspension for delinquent state tax under Neb. Rev. Stat. 77-377.01, and an accepted federal OIC is often used to justify a comparable state installment plan or waiver.",
